<article>
    <h1>FA&#xAD;CIL&#xAD;I&#xAD;TIES EN&#xAD;ABLE GREENER LIFE&#xAD;STYLE</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201010/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-10-10"><time>2020-10-10</time></a>
        - <span>HOME</span>
        - <span role="byline">Michelle Ng</span>
    </section>

    <p>HAR­NESS­ING SO­LAR EN­ERGY</p>
    <p>What: So­lar pan­els on the roofs of Hous­ing Board blocks in Pung­gol gen­er­ate en­ergy to power com­mon ser­vices like lift oper­a­tions and light­ing in com­mon ar­eas, with en­ergy-sav­ing LED light­ing also in use.</p>
    <p>To­tal en­ergy sav­ings:</p>
    <p>82.6 gi­gawatt hours per year, enough to power 17,200 four-room flats a year.</p>
    <p>SAV­ING WA­TER</p>
    <p>What: New flats in Pung­gol come with wa­ter-ef­fi­cient fit­tings to re­duce house­hold wa­ter con­sump­tion. Within hous­ing projects, an ur­ban wa­ter har­vest­ing sys­tem col­lects and stores rain­wa­ter for non-potable uses, such as the wash­ing of cor­ri­dors and land­scape ir­ri­ga­tion.</p>
    <p>To­tal wa­ter sav­ings: 1,387,818 cu­bic me­tres per year, enough to fill 555 Olympic-sized swim­ming pools.</p>
    <p>MIN­IMIS­ING WASTE</p>
    <p>What: All blocks in Pung­gol have a cen­tralised re­cy­cling chute to pro­mote house­hold re­cy­cling.</p>
    <p>Amount of re­cy­clables col­lected: About 1,285 tonnes a year, the es­ti­mated weight of 89 dou­ble-decker buses.</p>
    <p>BIKE-FRIENDLY TOWN</p>
    <p>What: Pung­gol will have over 50km of cy­cling paths when the net­work is com­pleted. There will be con­ve­niently lo­cated dual bi­cy­cle racks to en­cour­age green com­mut­ing.</p>
    <p>At 5.2km per sq km, the com­pleted cy­cling net­work will also be denser than Helsinki’s 4.7km per sq km.</p>


